Reference-contexts: Another objective is to minimize the number of switching modes used, thus simplifying the switch. In this paper, we consider the multiple-period time-slot assignment (MP-TSA) problem of scheduling real-time periodic traffic through a crossbar switch. Liu and Layland <ref> [12] </ref> introduced the periodic message model that we use in this paper. In the periodic model, a message is generated periodically, and the deadline for transmission of a message is equal to its period. A schedule in which all messages meet their deadlines is called a feasible schedule. <p> Such a set of messages is said to be schedulable. It is well known that on a single link the earliest deadline first (EDF) and minimum laxity first (MLF) algorithms will find a feasible schedule whenever the link utilization is no more than 1.0 <ref> [12, 13] </ref>. <p> Liu and Layland <ref> [12] </ref> introduced the earliest-deadline-first (EDF) algorithm which during each slot schedules the message instance with the nearest deadline. They showed that whenever the utilization of the link is less than or equal to 1.0, all message instances scheduled according to the EDF algorithm meet their deadlines.
